Lokoja – The Kogi State government has confirmed the outbreak of Lassa fever in nine local government areas of the state with seven deaths from 41 reported cases from January to date. A statement issued by the Permanent Secretary, Ministry of Health, Mr. Alonge Daniel, which was made available to newsmen in Lokoja disclosed this on Thursday. The statement claimed that areas such as Idah, Ibaji, Lokoja, Ajaokuta, Ofu, Okene, Okehi, Kabba and Adavi have reported at least one confirmed case during this period. Mr. Alonge noted that the state Ministry of Health has responded appropriately and timely to the epidemic as are sult of Governor Yahaya Bello’s intervention by timely releasing funds to curb the outbreak. “The ministry is collaborating with other line ministries especially Ministry of Environment and Ministry of Agriculture and partners to curtail the outbreak and prevent further spread of the disease. “The Ministry of Health has carried out community sensitisation activities in the local government areas affected by the outbreak. “This is to enable them adopt healthy lifestyle, by keeping their environment clean, maintain high standard of personal hygiene and prevent rats from having access to their food items both at home and in market places,” he said. He also mentioned that the health workers in primary, secondary and tertiary health institutions have been adequately sensitised to have high index of suspicion for early diagnosis and treatment. POLL “Disease Surveillance and Notification Officers from the state Ministry of Health and local government areas are following up the situation for early case detection and timely reporting. “The efforts of the state government are yielding positive result as the outbreak is going down based on our data. Currently, there are two active asesins table condition and receiving treatment atIrrua Specialist Teaching Hospital while 32 cases have been treated and discharged.